<DOC><DOCNO> ZF310-625-718 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 625 718</DOCID><JOURNAL>Los Angeles Times  April 13 1991 v110 pD3 12 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FTC has widened its probe, Microsoft says. (Federal TradeCommission) (Technology)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lazzareschi, Carla.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Federal Trade Commission (FTC) is expanding its investigationof Microsoft Corp's business practices, according to a statementby the software publisher.andP;  The FTC's investigation grows out ofcomplaints about restraint of trade and unfair competition by theworld's largest microcomputer software producer.andP;  The main issueis whether Microsoft monopolizes or tries to monopolize themicrocomputer software, systems and peripheral markets, inviolation of anti-trust and other laws.andP;  The debate arises fromMicrosoft's control of microcomputer operating systems (MS-DOS andOS/2) while at the same time developing applications for thosesystems.andP;  Industry observers respond variously, from criticism ofMicrosoft for crushing small opponents, to cries of 'sour grapes,'aimed at those who cannot compete.andP;  Microsoft's stock is affectedby the investigation, dropping $3.75 per share on the day thelarger scope of the FTC's probe was announced.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (Investigations).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Topic:     United States. Federal Trade CommissionInvestigationsMonopoliesLegal IssuesAntitrust LawsRestraint of Trade.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>